Asignment 4: A Nuts Problem

Alex Ceccotti

02-05-2018

  • Introduction

Introduction

The Molokai Nut Company (MNC) makes four different products from macadamia nuts grown in the Hawaiian Islands:

  • chocolate-coated whole nuts (Whole),
  • chocolate-coated nut clusters (Cluster),
  • chocolate-coated nut crunch bars (Crunch), and
  • plain roasted nuts (Roasted).

The company is barely able to keep up with the increasing demand for these products. However, increasing raw material prices and foreign competition are forcing MNC to watch its margins to ensure it is operating in the most efficient manner possible.

Marketing Demands

To meet marketing demands for the coming week, MNC needs to produce

  • at least 1,000 pounds of the Whole product,
  • between 400 and 500 pounds of the Cluster product,
  • no more than 150 pounds of the Crunch product, and
  • no more than 200 pounds of Roasted product.

Production Requirements

Each pound of the Whole, Cluster, Crunch, and Roasted product contains, respectively, 60%, 40%, 20%, and 100% macadamia nuts with the remaining weight made up of chocolate coating.

The company has 1100 pounds of nuts and 800 pounds of chocolate available for use in the next week.

The various products are made using four different machines that hull the nuts, roast the nuts, coat the nuts in chocolate (if needed), and package the products.

The following table summarizes the time required by each product on each machine. Each machine has 60 hours of time available in the coming week.

Minutes Required per Pound

Questions

  1. Do you agree with the controller’s recommendation? Why or why not?
require(knitr)
f = data.frame(whole=c(5304,3296,1266,1040),
                       cluster=c(1800,1280,609,500),
                       crunch=c(510,338,182,150),
                       roasted=c(925,660,243,200))
rownames(f)=c("revenue","variable_costs","fixed_costs","units")
f = as.data.frame(t(f))
f$net_profit = (f$revenue - f$variable_costs - f$fixed_costs) / f$units
f$variable_profit = (f$revenue - f$variable_costs) / f$units
kable(round(f,3))
revenue variable_costs fixed_costs units net_profit variable_profit
whole 5304 3296 1266 1040 0.713 1.931
cluster 1800 1280 609 500 -0.178 1.040
crunch 510 338 182 150 -0.067 1.147
roasted 925 660 243 200 0.110 1.325

Considering only the net profit we can’t conclude a lot, because it could be that increasing the quantity of a product with high fixed cost, its net profit will increase more then the others. So, we need to calculate the unit profit without include the fixed costs (variable_profit in the table above). Looking at this measure, we can say that Cluster and Crunch products are less profitable then the others (and they also get a negative net profit). So, the controller’s recommendation sounds well.

  1. Formulate a LP model for this problem.
  1. Create a executable model in R for this problem and solve it.
library(lpSolveAPI)
model = make.lp(0,4)
lp.control(model, sense="max")
set.objfn(model,obj=c(1.93,1.04,1.15,1.33))
row.add.mode(model,"on")

add.constraint(model,
               xt=c(0.6,0.4,0.2,1),
               type="<=",rhs=1100,
               indices=c(1:4))
add.constraint(model,
               xt=c(0.4,0.6,0.8),
               type="<=",rhs=800,
               indices=c(1:3))
add.constraint(model,
               xt=c(1,1,1,1),
               type="<=",rhs=3600,
               indices=c(1:4))
add.constraint(model,
               xt=c(2,1.5,1,1.75),
               type="<=",rhs=3600,
               indices=c(1:4))
add.constraint(model,
               xt=c(1,0.7,0.2),
               type="<=",rhs=3600,
               indices=c(1:3))
add.constraint(model,
               xt=c(2.5,1.6,1.25,1),
               type="<=",rhs=3600,
               indices=c(1:4))

row.add.mode(model,"off")
set.bounds(model,lower=c(1000,400,0,0),upper=c(NA,500,150,200))
solve(model)

  1. What is the optimal solution?

The optimal solution is to produce 1029 units of Whole, 400 units of Cluster, 150 units of Crunch and 200 units of Roasted. The total net profit will be 540.47 dollars.

  1. Perform the sensitivity analysis for this solution and answer the following questions.
printSensitivityObj(model)
  Objs          Sensitivity
1   C1    -inf <= C1 <= 2.3
2   C2 -inf <= C2 <= 1.2352
3   C3   0.965 <= C3 <= inf
4   C4   0.772 <= C4 <= inf

Which indicates that the base will remain if:

-inf <= c1 <= 2.3 (at now c1 = 1.93)

-inf <= c2 <= 1.24 (at now c2 = 1.04)

0.97 <= c3 <= inf (at now c3 = 1.15)

0.77 <= c4 <= inf (at now c4 = 1.33)

printSensitivityRHS(model,4)
  Rhs duals            Sensitivity
1  B1 0.000      -inf <= B1 <= inf
2  B2 0.000      -inf <= B2 <= inf
3  B3 0.000      -inf <= B3 <= inf
4  B4 0.000      -inf <= B4 <= inf
5  B5 0.000      -inf <= B5 <= inf
6  B6 0.772 3527.5 <= B6 <= 3777.5

Which indicates that all the dual variables, except from the last one, are equal to 0 (zero shadow prices mean that small changes in nuts & chocolate availability and in hulling, roasting & coating machine time availability not affect the solution). On the other hand, the increasing by 1 minute the packaging machine time availability will improve the optimal value by 0.77 (but the base remains only if that time will be less than 3777.5 and greather than 3527.5). From this analysis we can see that the optimal solution is mostly dictated by the boundaries.

  1. Is the solution degenerate?

No it isn’t beacause the last constraint has an allowable increase or decrease different from 0.

  1. Is the solution unique?
write.lp(model, "mymodel", type="lp")
rc<-solve(model)
sols<-list()
obj0<-get.objective(model)

while(TRUE) {
   sol <- round(get.variables(model))
   sols <- c(sols,list(sol))
   add.constraint(model,2*sol-1,"<=", sum(sol)-1)
   rc<-solve(model)
   if (rc!=0) break;
   if (get.objective(model)<obj0-1e-6) break;
}
sols
[[1]]
[1] 1029  400  150  200

Yes, the solution is unique.

  1. If MNC wanted to decrease the production of any product, which one would you recommend and why?

I would recommend to decrease the production of Cluster nuts because that product has the lowest margin between price and variable costs (c2 coefficient) and its quantity in the optimal solution lays on the lower bound.

  1. If MNC wanted to increase the production of any product, which one would you recommend and why?

I would recommend to increase the production of Roasted nuts because that product has the highest margin between price and variable costs (c4 coefficient) if we consider the products with an upper bound.

The time availability of tha packaging machine is preventing them to make more money. They should acquire 177.5 minutes (value from the sensitivity analysis) and they should pay at most 0.772 per minute (value from the sensitivity analysis).

  1. How much should MNC be willing to pay to acquire more chocolate?

Nothing, because it has zero dual value.

  1. If the marketing department wanted to decrease the price of the Whole product by $0.25, would the optimal solution change?
model <- read.lp("mymodel", type="lp")
old_price <- (f$revenue/f$units)[1]
new_price <- old_price - 0.25
var_costs <- (f$variable_costs/f$units)[1]
(new_margin <- new_price - var_costs)
[1] 1.680769
set.objfn(model,obj=c(new_margin,1.04,1.15,1.33))
solve(model)
[1] 0
get.variables(model)
[1] 1029  400  150  200

No, the optimal solution would not change (because the margin of the Whole nuts will continue to be higher than the others).
